# plurnk-bench config — the shipped legend: every knob + its default.
#
# plurnk-bench is a CLIENT of the plurnk daemon: it drives benchmark tasks through
# @plurnk/plurnk, which connects to a running plurnk-service daemon. Engine config
# (models, providers, turns) lives in the DAEMON's environment — the ~/.plurnk cascade,
# NOT here. This file holds only what the bench process itself reads.
#
# Override order (low → high precedence):
#   ./.env.example  (this floor — override, don't remove!)
#   < ./.env        (per-checkout config)
#   < --env-file=…
#   < shell environment
# Feature-flag bools use `=== "1"` exactly, never `=== "true"`.

# --- Daemon connection (consumed by @plurnk/plurnk) ---
# The one knob the client needs: the daemon WebSocket URL. The bench never starts a
# daemon; it attaches to one already running (`plurnk-service start`).
PLURNK_WS=ws://127.0.0.1:3044

# --- Daemon / model config is NOT here ---
# Bench does NOT re-declare the daemon's config. The Pier smoke (deepswe/smoke.sh) reads
# it from the authoritative sources in place:
#   • model layer   ← ~/.plurnk/.env         (PLURNK_MODEL, PLURNK_MODEL_<alias>, GBNF)
#   • provider env  ← your shell (.bashrc)    (OPENAI_BASE_URL, XAI_*, keys, …)
# and forwards them to the in-container daemon via --agent-env. Every knob is documented
# in plurnk-service/.env.example. Pick the model with `deepswe/smoke.sh <task> <alias>`.

# --- Bench's own knobs (PLURNK_BENCH_ namespace; smoke.sh orchestration, never forwarded) ---
# All bench-invented config is namespaced PLURNK_BENCH_ to respect the global env and to
# stay distinct from the daemon's PLURNK_* config that we merely carry.
# PLURNK_BENCH_TIMEOUT_SEC=   # client timeout override; default = task's [agent] budget − headroom
# PLURNK_BENCH_CPUS=          # container cpu override; default = task native (leaderboard-compliant)
# PLURNK_BENCH_FORCE_BUILD=   # =1 to force an agent-image rebuild (after a @plurnk version bump)
# PLURNK_BENCH_NO_GBNF=       # =1 drop PLURNK_PROVIDERS_GBNF (models that can't enforce it, e.g. xai/grok)
